Bolivia, a landlocked country, is still alive with memories of the lost coast, which Chile lost in a bloody conflict over resources in the 19th century, and there is a strong desire to re-wind the waves of the Pacific Ocean.
These hopes are perhaps the strongest for decades, as Bolivia is awaiting the verdict of the International Court of Justice, which will conclude five years of deliberations.
“Bolivia has the ball, which infuses people with a spirit of togetherness and peace, who are waiting in a positive mood for the outcome,” said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
