John Edward: Language is essential for global citizens
Scottish independent schools have a tradition of providing excellent education. Looking at the recent outstanding exam results, this situation has not changed in 2018, which is further strengthened by individual and group successes in sports, arts, music and other community initiatives.
In Scotland, more than 30,000 students are already studying in such institutions, represented by The Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), which aim to provide students and parents with the best possible service.
Independent schools strive to prepare students for further education, higher education, their chosen careers, and their positions as citizens of the world.
In an education sector where it is possible to design and implement customized school curricula, we see that modern languages continue to prove popular and sought-after subjects.
Nelson Mandela once said, “If you talk to someone in a language they understand, it goes to their head.
But if you speak in his language, it goes to his heart.”
This is an important reminder, because we cannot rely on English alone to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
This year’s exam results show that students from independent schools all over the country brought the best results from foreign languages.
Sixty-eight per cent of all students studying a foreign language achieved a higher A grade (above 85 per cent).
Data collected from 74 SCIS member schools showed that 72 percent of students received a higher A grade in Mandarin, while 72 percent of German students, 69 percent of French students, and 63 percent of Spanish students achieved an A grade.
These results confirm that independent schools in Scotland see foreign languages as essential knowledge, which children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Today, languages have become as important as natural sciences, technology, engineering and mathematics in both independent and non-independent schools.
A 2014 survey by the UK Commission on Employment and Vocational Training found that 17% of employers say filling vacancies is difficult because of a lack of language skills.
From this we can see that language skills are becoming more and more necessary for young people to have successful careers.
As more and more workplaces demand knowledge of foreign languages, language skills are essential in a globalised world.
Regardless of what career you choose, if you have learned a foreign language, you will acquire a lifelong knowledge that will give you a clear advantage.
Being able to communicate directly with other nationalities automatically gives the multi-lingual candidate a competitive advantage.
According to a YouGov survey of 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75 percent of respondents did not speak a single foreign language well enough to engage with others, and French was the only language spoken by more than 10 percent (15 percent) of respondents.
Therefore, it is important to place emphasis on the language education of children even now.
Speaking several languages, especially in developing countries, can be a tool for children to be equipped with to better compete for important jobs as adults.
Each school in Scotland will have a different language.
Many schools will focus on classical modern languages, while others will teach languages such as Mandarin or Japanese that are expected to be of paramount importance to the UK by 2020.
Whatever your child’s area of interest, you’ll be able to study multiple elective languages at independent schools and be trained by tutors who are experts in their field.
Scottish independent schools are committed to creating a learning environment that equips and equips children with the skills they will need to succeed, whatever the future holds.
It’s not hard to see that in today’s global business environment, languages remain vital to a country’s future, and education should reflect that.
As a matter of fact, knowledge of modern languages should rather be treated as ‘international communication skills’.
Independent schools offer young people in Scotland the choice, diversity and quality of education.
Il faut bien le faire – this is how it should be.
John Edward, President of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
