“In the absence of trust in America, we feel that the security of our nation is not assured, and under these circumstances there is no way that we will be the first to disarm unilaterally.”
While Ri reiterated North Korea’s disappointment at Washington’s resistance to the idea of “progressive” nuclear disarmament, which would see North Korea rewarded for the steps taken so far, his statement seemed significant because he did not unequivocally reject unilateral nuclear disarmament, as Pyongyang has done so far.
Ri referred to a joint statement made by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first-ever summit between a US president in power and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, in which Kim promised to work on “the denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula” while Trump guaranteed the integrity of North Korea.
North Korea is seeking an official end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States says Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
