Harvard Students Are Educated to Get Enough Rest
A new class at Harvard University this year has encouraged students to get more sleep, fighting against the growing macho culture of caffeine-fuelled, all-night learning.
One academic concluded that students at the world’s number one university are often completely lost when it comes to how they should care for themselves.
The course, which he said was the first of its kind in the United States, was designed by Professor Charles Czeisler, who teaches sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and practices as a specialist at Brigham and Women’s Hospital.
What inspired the course to be developed was that he had previously given a lecture on the effects of sleep deprivation on learning.
“At the end, a girl came up to me and asked, ‘Why am I just now facing this as a senior?’
He said no one ever talked to him about the importance of sleep, which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
Launched for the first time this year, the course will show students how good sleep habits have a fundamental impact on their academic and athletic performance, as well as a positive impact on their overall well-being.
According to Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and director of the university’s health service, the university decided to start the course because the students were found to be extremely sleep-deprived during the week.
The one-hour course also includes a series of interactive exercises.
In one, for example, they show a picture of a dorm room where students can click on coffee cups, curtains, sneakers, and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light, how sports performance is affected by sleep deprivation, and why the bedtime routine is important.
In another section, participants are described how long-term sleep deprivation increases the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
They will present a map of the campus area with interactive icons to encourage participants to think about their daily routines.
“We don’t want to change the behavior of our students.
But we believe they have a right to this knowledge – just as they have a right to know the health effects of smoking,” said Prof. Czeisler.
The culture of learning through the night is still flourishing, he said, adding that modern technology and the ever-increasing pressure on students mean that sleep deprivation is a growing problem.
Sufficient and quality sleep is a student’s “secret weapon” in the fight against stress, exhaustion, and anxiety, and even protects against obesity, as sleep deprivation forces the brain into starvation mode and causes a constant sense of hunger.
Raymond So helped design the course for Professor Czeisler, a 19-year-old California student studying chemistry and biophysics, who was the first to take one of the professor’s courses at Harvard last year.
He said what he heard there opened his eyes and encouraged him to pursue a university-level education.
He hopes that, as a next step, postgraduate students will also be able to participate in a similar training programme before finding employment in the private sector.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students set a bedtime alert, an alarm for waking up, and learn about the harmful effects of “blue light” emitted by electric screens and LED light sources, which can easily throw them off their daily rhythm and make it difficult to fall asleep.
