What is the Global Citizen Festival and has it managed to reduce poverty?
The annual New York City music festival, Global Citizen Festival, kicks off on Saturday with stars from around the world standing up for a truly noble cause: the global eradication of poverty.
The Global Citizen Festival will be held for the seventh time, and tens of thousands of people are expected to spend the Great Lawn of Central Park, where participants can not only enjoy the performances of Janet Jackson, Cardi B or Shawn Mendes, but also draw attention to the real purpose of the event: the eradication of extreme poverty by 2030.
The Global Citizen Festival was first held in 2012 as part of the Global Poverty project, which is run by an international advocacy group that aims to eradicate poverty by actively involving more people in the fight against poverty.
Free tickets to the concert (unless they are willing to pay for a VIP ticket) can be given to those who undertake certain tasks or “actions”, such as volunteering, sending an email to a senior politician, a phone call or any other meaningful activity to raise awareness of the project’s goal: the eradication of poverty.
But how successful has Global Citizen been in achieving its goals over the past 12 years?
Is it really an effective way to reward people with concert tickets to convince others of the importance of action, or is it just another form of so-called “clicktivism” where people feel they have made a meaningful contribution to a cause by signing an online petition or writing a Twitter message?
Since 2011, Global Citizen data shows that more than 19 million “actions” have been carried out by project sponsors for a variety of purposes.
These actions have contributed to global leaders dedicating $37 billion to anti-poverty policies and commitments that could impact the lives of more than 2.25 billion people by 2030.
In early 2018, the group claimed that 390 commitments and announcements came from their actions, of which $10 billion had already been paid out or raised through fundraising.
The group estimated that the money raised had a direct impact on the lives of nearly 649 million people.
The main commitments include The Power of Nutrition, a UK-based partnership of investors and contractors that aims to “help children reach their full potential.” The organization pledged $35 million to Rwanda to help end hunger after receiving more than 4,700 Twitter messages from “global citizens.”
“With the support of the UK government and donors, national governments and global citizens like you, we can place social injustice and malnutrition among the footnotes in history books,” said Tracey Ullman, Ambassador of Power of Nutrition to the crowd at a live concert in London in April 2018.
The group also claims that after asking the UK in more than 5,000 acts to improve the nutrition of mothers and their children, the government has earmarked funds for the Power of Nutrition project, which will improve the nutrition of 5 million women and children.
One of the frequently asked questions posted on the Global Citizen website is “Why do you think extreme poverty can be eradicated?”.
The Global Citizen responded: “It will be a long and difficult road, sometimes we get stuck and sometimes we fail.
But like previous civil rights and anti-segregation movements, we will achieve our goal because together we are stronger.”
