Donggala Governorate is more than 300 km long on the northwestern coast of the island of Celebes.
The population of the province – a smaller administrative region than the province – was about 299,200 in 2017.
Central Celebes is dominated by fishing and farming, especially in the coastal areas of Donggala.
Nickel mining is an important sector of the economy, but it is concentrated mainly in Morowali, on the other side of Celebes.
According to the Indonesian Disaster Management Agency, Palut and Donggala have been hit by a series of tsunamis over the past 100 years.
A 1938 tsunami killed more than 200 residents and destroyed hundreds of houses in Donggala.
In 1996, a tsunami hit West Donggala, killing nine people.
Indonesia is located in the geologically active Pacific Ring of Fire, so earthquakes are common.
Just a few of the major earthquakes and tsunamis of recent years:
2004: On December 26, a massive sea storm began off the west coast of Aceh province in northern Sumatra, triggering a tsunami that reached 14 countries, killing a total of 226,000 people along the Indian Ocean coastline, with more than half of the victims killed in Aceh.
2005: A series of strong quakes hit the west coast of Sumatra between late March and early April.
Hundreds of people died on the island of Nias, near Sumatra.
2006: A magnitude 6.8 quake struck the southern part of Java, Indonesia's largest island, and the resulting tsunami claimed almost 700 lives on the southern coast.
2009: A 7.6 magnitude earthquake struck near Padang, the capital of Western Sumatra province.
More than 1,100 people lost their lives.
2010: A magnitude 7.5 quake struck an island in the Mentawai Archipelago near Sumatra, triggering a 10-meter-tall tsunami that destroyed dozens of villages and killed about 300 people.
2016: A near-surface quake hits Aceh Pidie Jaya's governorship, causing panic and destruction in the wake of the devastating 2004 tsunami.
